			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Wow, so many misconceptions and misunderstandings about the Warrior job, I had to register!  My main job is a level 50 Paladin, but I recently got done leveling my subjob (Warrior) up to 37 so that I can concentrate on getting to 75 with Paladin.  Saying that Warrior is only a "Shield" aka tank is uninformed at best.
<br />

<br />
Warrior is a versatile and very powerful job, IMO one of the strongest in the game.  But trying to classify it as either a "Sword" or "Shield" is misguided, because what makes Warrior so powerful is that it can act as either ... and do it well.  The problem with people's perception of Warrior is that most people use Warrior as a stepping stone to get to their "Advanced" jobs, and so never try to bring out the potential of the class.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Tanking</span>
<br />
The "Shield."  Everyone seems big on Warriors tanking, but seems to think that they can't hold hate; however, it is very easy to hold hate in a party from 10-37 as a War/Mnk (War/Thf or War/Nin takes some juggling to hold hate at this level).  How easily could you hold hate if you could Provoke twice as often?  Well, Boost (Mnk 5) acts as a mini-Provoke (maybe 1/3 of a Provoke) and can be used twice as often as Provoke.  Dodge (Mnk 15) acts as an emergency hate-grabber, as does Warcry (War 35).  Also, Counter's always nice when tanking, though it's very inconsistent.  The biggest problem is that you may generate so much hate (Provoke + Boost + Damage) that the other players can't get the mob off of you if you get in trouble.
<br />

<br />
A well-equipped War/Mnk won't take much more damage than a Paladin (maybe slightly less than a Pld if you use Defender, which isn't always recommended), but you'll require slightly more healing because you can't self-heal.  Also, depending on your party setup, it may be beneficial for you to use Great Axe to tank (yes, eat a little extra damage), just so you can throw Shield Break at the beginning of a fight.  I would mainly do this if one skillchaining DD was lagging behind in TP consistently.  That and make the Rdm cast Gravity and the Blm cast Frost if melees are consistently missing the mob.
<br />

<br />
Now, on to ...
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Damage Dealing</span>
<br />
The infamous "Sword."  Regardless of what you think or have been told, Warriors can deal heavy damage.  Most, however, never equip their character to properly act as a competitor to other DD classes.  I never fail to laugh when I see a War/Rdm equipped with a Great Sword or Scythe complain that he can't deal damage.  Actually, sometimes I cry, but that's another matter.  To those who think a Warrior can't deal damage, though, I have two words to say, "Great Axe."
<br />

<br />
Great Axe has one of the highest Damage/Delay ratios in the game, and it's Warrior's A+ weapon.  Warrior gets Berserk at level 15.  From 15-25, this combined with attack oriented gear, Great Axe, and food is enough to put them in the top tier of melee damagers (at 23, Warrior gets Sturmwind, a VERY nice weaponskill).  At level 25, Warriors get Double Attack, which ups their damage even further.  At level 30, other classes catch up with a lot of job abilities, including from subjobs.  This is when you need to start using War/Thf when you're not tanking.
<br />

<br />
With a good Great Axe at level 30, you will be hitting for 70-90 damage per hit while Berserked (as a Hume); criticals are typically around 120 damage.  Sneak Attack + Sturmwind, at level 30+, is simply godly.  250 damage, <span style="font-style: italic">easily</span>.  270-300 is fairly common.  I've had mine max out at 380 when Double Attack fired during the weaponskill (~lvl 34).  Actually, 480, but that was with Mighty Strikes active, so it doesn't count.  This is NOT counting added damage from a skillchain.  You have to play carefully, because MOST tanks (including some Paladins) cannot hold hate over the type of damage you can do if you're stupid about it.
<br />

<br />
I parsed a series of battles recently playing as a War/Thf (from levels 35-37 in one party).  I consistently did around 25-40% (average, 32%) of the group's damage per fight, while playing with a rank 6 Sam/War and Tarutaru Blm/Whm.  Now the Tarutaru Blm COULD have outdamaged me hands down if he put his mind to it, but probably not without consistently drawing aggro.  I was ALREADY drawing aggro depending mainly on just how accurate I was in any given fight (high accuracy fight = aggro by the end, but ~40% damage).
<br />

<br />
Eventually, the Sam/War had to leave.  We replaced him with a Drk/War.  What happened to damage?  Well, the Drk/War consistently did around 20% (average player, our Sam was amazing).  I did around 27-40%, and our Blm/Whm made up the difference and took hate a few times.
<br />

<br />
Now the point of this post is not to get into some sort of contest with other jobs ("No, I can deal more damage than Warrior any day of the week! Rawr!"), but rather to provide some in game experience to show that Warrior CAN act as an effective "Sword", from level 10-50 at least.  I say 50, because one of the last parties I was in as a Pld/War was with a 50 War/Thf, which is where I got the (bright) idea that I should try it out for when I wasn't tanking while leveling my subjob.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Why haven't I ever seen what you're talking about?</span>
<br />
1.) <span style="font-style: italic">Weapon selection:</span>  As a Warrior, you need to have multiple weapons skilled up.  Preferably Axe (tanking) and Great Axe (DD and occasionally for tanking).  Scythe weaponskills are poor until Guillotine (which you never get as a Warrior), compared to Great Axe.  Great Sword weaponskills are better, but still don't compare.  Sword doesn't do as much damage as Axe when tanking (having tanked extensively with both), and the only time I used it as Warrior was to start Fusion with a Mnk or Thf/Mnk partner (Red Lotus Blade &gt;&gt; Combo).
<br />
2.) <span style="font-style: italic">Gear:</span>  You need TWO sets of gear.  Yes, that's right, two if you want to do it right.  One set is mainly +Def/Vit/Agi gear for tanking with just enough +Acc/Dex to hit the mob.  The other is +Attack/Accuracy/Str/Dex gear for DD.  If you want to come close to a Drk in damage, you need to equip yourself like a Drk does (ever seen a Drk with +Vit rings?).  If you try to mix and match (some +Def, some +Atk) you will be a mediocre tank and a mediocre damage dealer.  Sorry.
<br />
3.) <span style="font-style: italic">Players:</span>  Warrior is a standard job, and as such, it's one of the first jobs many people take to 18, and then 30.  This means the majority of Warriors you see from 1-30 are new players who are still learning the game, and generally are cash strapped (see #2).  Also, many people view Warrior as only a stepping stone to some other, better, job (Drk, Pld, Sam, Rng, Nin, etc.).  Luckily, I leveled Whm to 30 first, so by the time I came back to Warrior, I wanted to see if it could truly kick ass and take names.  It does.
<br />
4.) <span style="font-style: italic">Subjobs:</span>  From personal experience, War/Mnk is a good tank, but mediocre DD.  War/Nin is an excellent half-tank, half-DD.  War/Thf is a good damage dealer, but mediocre tank.  If you want to have versatility, you need to have multiple subjobs leveled all the way up, so you can switch from tank to DD and back depending on what your party wants.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, in regards to the "Sword/Shield" ("Great Axe/Shield?") question, my answer is "Either, depending on the situation."</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
